  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Establishes global standards for combating money laundering\n- Recommends legal and regulatory measures\n- Works with countries to implement anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n- Provide frameworks for international cooperation in preventing money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Sets international banking standards\n- Provides guidelines for detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Offers recommendations for preventing financial crimes\n- Assists countries in developing AML regulations\n\n5. Individual Countries' Laws\n- Many nations have specific anti-money laundering legislation\n- Examples include the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act and EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nThese regulations typically require financial institutions to:\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement robust compliance programs\n\nPenalties for non-compliance can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
